{
  "texts": [
    "VGG-16 (Simonyan and Zisserman, 2015), GoogleNet (Jahandad et al., 2019), ResNet (Jafar and Lee, 2021), DenseNet (G. Huang et al., 2017), Genetic CNN (Xie and Alan, 2017), SqueezeNet (Iandola et al., 2016), LeNet (LeCun et al., 1999), Inception (LeCun et al., 1999), MobileNet (Howard et al., 2017), and Xception (Chollet, 2017) are a few examples.",
    "Plant pathology divides plant diseases into biotic and abiotic diseases.",
    "The fungus, bacteria, insects, and viruses cause biotic diseases (Figure 3).",
    "Non-living causes like environmental nutritional deficits, chemical imbalances, metal toxicity, and physical traumas produce abiotic disorders (Husin et al., 2012).",
    "Plants can also show signs of abiotic diseases when exposed to unfavorable environmental conditions such as high temperatures, excessive moisture, inadequate light, a lack of essential nutrients, an acidic soil pH, or even greenhouse gases (Figure 3)."
  ]
}